AB  - Background: Climate change has contributed to environmental changes that significantly impact on the agriculture sector. Each year, temperature and precipitation anomalies devastate agricultural production in multiple Caribbean countries. With the outlook of rising heat in the Caribbean and harsher droughts, affordable and effective adaptation is explored for the sustainability of the sector. This project was a pilot intended to seek solutions for farmers in Grenada to maintain crop production and high yields during the dry season and drought. Method: In the experiment, an engineered glass product, in powder and granule forms, was introduced to soils with two cultivated crops under greenhouse conditions. After establishment, the plants were exposed to drought-like conditions. Soil water content and biomass yield of beans (Phaseolus vulgaris) and pok choi (Brassica rapa) were measured in two experimental groups, compared to a control group. Results: The control soil samples retained a mean of 0.10 g g(-1) water per mass of soil, and both granule and powder samples retained a mean of 0.12 g g(-1) water per mass of soil. Among the pok choi samples, the mean biomass yield in plants with the powder grade was slightly higher than in samples with the granule grade and control plants. The differences in the means were not statistically significant (p = 0.603). Differences in the mean values in treatment groups and between the treatment and control groups were not significant (p > 0.05). The decreased mean weight of the beans in the third harvesting period was significantly different from the mean weight in the first harvesting period (p < 0.001). Overall, the mean weight of the beans in all groups declined from the first harvesting period. Conclusion: While there is some promise to enhance soil water retention, there is still insufficient evidence to conclude that the application of the product will be revolutionary for climate change adaptation. Further studies are needed in natural farming environments to more accurately determine the potential of the product to retain soil water and enhance biomass yield in Grenada.
