AB  - Sub-Saharan Africa (SSA) is the most food insecure sub-region globally. For some time now, the debate about addressing hunger in this area of the continent has been pitted between ecological agriculture and input intensification. The latter school has gained traction under the New Green Revolution (NGR) for Africa program, aiming to modernize African smallholder agriculture to achieve higher yields. Since its inception in 2006, there has been a longstanding debate over its effectiveness - a debate which impinges upon the broader question of the future of food in a rapidly changing climate. This study systematically reviews empirical literature on the outcomes of NGR initiatives in SSA to understand its livelihood and environmental impacts. A total of 364 studies were screened, of which 39 were deemed relevant. Positive impacts discussed included grain yield and profit increases from crops promoted by the NGR. The majority of studies, however, documented negative outcomes, including social differentiation as a result of the relegation of the poor who cannot afford subsidized synthetic inputs. We argue this model does not hold sufficient promise for a sustainable food future for the sub-region. Global funding streams should prioritize alternative ecological agricultural development models aligned with poorer smallholder farmers' realities.
