AB  - Comparing the yields obtained in the main and successive corn crops represents an important study for evaluating the adaptability of hybrids to different vegetation conditions and for substantiating technological recommendations for farmers and the selection of optimal genetic material. In the context of climate change and the need to optimize the use of agricultural land, successive crops are gaining increasing importance, allowing the use of the summer-autumn period by obtaining additional production. In this study, the behavior of 5 corn hybrids from the FAO 240-280 maturity groups was monitored regarding productivity in the main and successive crops, quality indices such as hectoliter mass and thousand-grain mass, but also production components such as the number of rows of grains per cob and the number of grains per row, components that determine the future harvest. In the conditions of 2024, the productions achieved in the successive crop exceeded the values obtained in the main crop, which demonstrates the increased potential of the successive crop in areas with favorable thermal and pluviometric resources. The semi-early hybrids have proven to be efficient in the successive system, effectively capitalizing on the short vegetation period. Among the variants studied, the Lid 2020 c and Danubio hybrids recorded the greatest production increases, and this behavior recommends them for successive cultivation, while Norico stood out for its stable production, being an option for both cultivation systems.
