TI  - Intersectional vulnerabilities in disaster resilience: Gender, geography, and poverty in Zimbabwe's agrarian communities
T2  - INTERNATIONAL JOURNAL OF DISASTER RISK REDUCTION
LA  - English
KW  - Gender
KW  - Intersectionality
KW  - Resilience trap
KW  - Sendai framework
KW  - Spatial inequity
AB  - Climate change intensifies disaster risks in agrarian communities, yet vulnerabilities shaped by intersecting gender, geographic, and socio-economic inequities remain understudied in rural Africa. Focusing on Chikombedzi (Ward 12), a severely marginalised agrarian enclave in Zim-babwe's Chiredzi District, this mixed-methods study employs a convergent parallel design, integrating quantitative surveys (n =360) and qualitative interviews/focus group discussions (n =68), to unravel how these axes compound disaster vulnerability. Results reveal stark disparities: women shoulder 92 % of water collection (4-6 h/day) and 69 % of subsistence farming, yet own only 15 % of land. Female-headed households endure 70 % food insecurity during disasters compared to 50 % of male-headed households, while remoteness isolates 85 % of villages from timely flood aid. Spatial inequities trap communities in high-risk dependencies, with 78 % relying on firewood, exacerbating deforestation. This study provides the first intersectional analysis of disaster resilience in rural Africa, demonstrating how patriarchal norms, infrastructural neglect, and poverty intersect to entrench systemic exclusion. Our findings underscore the urgent need for intersectionality-informed policies that integrate gender equity, spatial justice, and participatory governance into disaster risk reduction (DRR) efforts. Transformative solutions, including land tenure reforms and participatory governance, are proposed, aligning with Sendai Framework Priorities 3 (investing in disaster risk reduction) and 4 (enhancing preparedness and response). This research advances scalable models for equitable resilience in climate-vulnerable agrarian contexts by centring marginalised voices.
