AB  - This study was conducted in Siddipet district, Telangana state, India. It assesses agroforestry impact through a multistage systematic random sampling with 5% intensity, i.e. 25 villages from 499, selecting three agroforestry farmers per village from four categories - marginal, small, semi-medium, and medium. Siddipet was chosen for its agroforestry prevalence, favorable climate, and diverse farm sizes. Eight agroforestry systems were identified, with Boundary + Scattered being the most common (24.67%) and Block + Boundary + Scattered the least preferred (2.67%). A total of 59 tree species from 29 families were recorded, 86.44% being indigenous. Predominant species included Tectona grandis and Mangifera indica. Bund planting had the highest biomass (528.91 kg tree(- 1)), while Block + Boundary + Scattered had the lowest (34.09 t ha(- 1)) and the lowest grain yield (5.83 t ha(- 1)) but achieved the highest net returns (Indian Rupee177,689.7 ha(- 1)) and benefit-cost ratio (2.02). Scattered planting had the lowest net returns (Indian Rupee55,066.9 ha(- 1)) and BCR (1.73). Carbon sequestration was highest in Bund + Boundary (7.75 t ha(- 1)) and lowest in sole crops (4.85 t ha(- 1)), while sole crops had the highest grain yield (6.42 t ha(- 1)). Agroforestry adoption in Siddipet depends on economic and ecological factors, with species richness enhancing sustainability.
