AB  - Currently, the total utilization rate of iron and steel solid waste in China is low, only about 60%. Few studies focused on the environmental impact analysis of dust sludge utilization that is generally difficult to reuse. This study used the process-LCA method to evaluate the melting reduction technology for iron and steel waste residues in a steel plant of Tangshan. The results reveal that the GWP accounts for the 46% of total environmental impact, followed by AP (32%) and PED (15%). Furthermore, the directly on-site CO2 emission accounts for the 65.95% of the total emissions, much higher than the upstream emission, attributing to the coke combustion from the Melting Reduction Modification (MRM) process and coal consumption for power generation. Such findings can provide vital scientific evidence for steel and iron slag reuse so that more appropriate reuse strategies can be proposed by taking the melting reduction technology as a reference.
