TI  - Multi-objective optimization of crop land allocation for sustainability within the food-energy-water-land-fertilizer (FEWLF) nexus
T2  - COMPUTERS & CHEMICAL ENGINEERING
LA  - English
KW  - Sustainable agriculture
KW  - Greenhouse gas emission
KW  - Farmers' income
KW  - Water security
KW  - Fertilizer consumption
KW  - Optimum land allocation
KW  - DEMAND
AB  - Higher agricultural productivity is essential for meeting the food and energy security of the growing population. However, it led to excessive use of inorganic fertilizers, pesticides, and advanced seed varieties which also contributed to challenges such as greenhouse gas emissions, climate change, soil and water pollution, food toxicity, and resource depletion. This study introduces a novel optimization framework utilizing a lexicographic approach to optimize land allocation, fertilizer use, Minimum Support Price (MSP) of agricultural products, and biomass-based energy production. In this study, we propose a food-energy-water-land-fertilizer (FEWLF) nexus, extending the food-energy-water nexus, that integrates the environmental, social, and economic dimensions of sustainability. By incorporating a multi-objective optimization framework, it aims to maximize food production value, improve farmers' Benefit-Cost Ratio (BCR), and mitigate environmental impacts, including greenhouse gas (GHG) emissions, groundwater consumption, and fertilizer use. The proposed model has been evaluated across diverse agroecological regions, including water-scarce, fertile, and high-rainfall areas, ensuring its adaptability. Results show that strategic land reallocation can reduce groundwater consumption by up to 90%, GHG emissions by up to 80%, and fertilizer emissions by up to 85% across the states of Rajasthan, Andhra Pradesh, and Bihar, in India, while simultaneously improving food production value, farmer incomes, and benefit-cost-ratio. This study highlights a comprehensive, optimization-based approach to advance sustainable agriculture, providing actionable insights into India's agricultural landscape and beyond.
